  "prompt": "What are some useful websites for students?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a breakdown of useful websites for students, categorized for easier browsing.  I've included a mix of free and subscription-based options, noting where relevant.\n\n**I. Academic Research & Learning:**\n\n*   **General Research:**\n    *   **Google Scholar:** (Free) Excellent for finding scholarly articles, theses, and books. Filter by date, author, and topic.\n    *   **JSTOR:** (Subscription often through university libraries, some open access content) A digital library of academic journals, books, and primary sources. Great for in-depth research.\n    *   **Internet Archive:** (Free)  A non-profit library of millions of free books, movies, music, and archived websites.  The Wayback Machine is invaluable for finding old versions of web pages.\n    *   **Project Gutenberg:** (Free) Offers over 60,000 free ebooks, primarily older works in the public domain.\n    *   **Khan Academy:** (Free)  Covers a wide range of subjects, from math and science to history and economics.  Excellent for video lessons and practice exercises.\n    *   **Wolfram Alpha:** (Free, with paid Pro version) A computational knowledge engine.  It can perform calculations, answer factual questions, and provide data analysis.\n    *   **Wikipedia:** (Free) While not a primary source, it's a good starting point for understanding a topic and finding links to more authoritative sources. Be sure to verify information from Wikipedia with other sources.\n    *   **Your University/College Library Website:** (Free to enrolled students)  Access to databases, journals, ebooks, and research guides.  Don't underestimate the resources available through your institution.\n\n*   **Specific Subjects:**\n    *   **Coursera/edX/Udacity:** (Free courses often available, paid certificates/degrees) Platforms offering courses from top universities and institutions.  Great for exploring new subjects or deepening your knowledge.\n    *   **MIT OpenCourseWare:** (Free) MIT makes course materials freely available online.\n    *   **PubMed Central:** (Free) A free archive of biomedical and life sciences literature.\n    *   **ERIC (Education Resources Information Center):** (Free) A comprehensive database of education-related literature.\n    *   **LibriVox:** (Free)  Audiobooks of books in the public domain read by volunteers.\n\n**II. Writing & Citation:**\n\n*   **Grammarly:** (Free version available, paid Premium version) Checks grammar, spelling, punctuation, and style. Offers suggestions for improvement.\n*   **ProWritingAid:** (Free version available, paid Premium version) Similar to Grammarly, but with more in-depth analysis of writing style.\n*   **Purdue OWL (Online Writing Lab):** (Free) A comprehensive resource for writing, grammar, and citation.\n*   **EasyBib/Cite This For Me/Zotero/Mendeley:** (Free and paid options) Citation generators and management tools.  Help you create citations in various styles (MLA, APA, Chicago, etc.) and organize your research. Zotero and Mendeley are also reference managers.\n\n**III. Productivity & Organization:**\n\n*   **Google Workspace (Docs, Sheets, Slides, Drive, Calendar):** (Free with a Google account) A suite of online productivity tools.\n*   **Microsoft Office Online (Word, Excel, PowerPoint):** (Free with a Microsoft account, more features with a subscription) Similar to Google Workspace.\n*   **Evernote/OneNote:** (Free and paid options) Note-taking apps that allow you to organize notes, web clippings, and other information.\n*   **Trello/Asana/Monday.com:** (Free and paid options) Project management tools that can help you organize assignments, collaborate with classmates, and track progress.\n*   **Forest/Freedom:** (Paid apps) Apps that help you block distracting websites and apps, allowing you to focus on your work.\n*   **Todoist/TickTick:** (Free and paid options) To-do list apps that help you manage tasks and deadlines.\n\n**IV. Skill Development & Career:**\n\n*   **LinkedIn Learning (formerly Lynda.com):** (Subscription often through university libraries, individual subscriptions available) Video courses on a wide range of professional skills, including software, business, and creative skills.\n*   **Codecademy/freeCodeCamp:** (Free and paid options) Learn to code with interactive tutorials.\n*   **Duolingo:** (Free, with paid Plus version) Learn a new language through gamified lessons.\n*   **Indeed/LinkedIn/Glassdoor:** Job search websites.  Also useful for researching companies and salaries.\n*   **Resume.io/Canva:** (Free and paid options) Resume builders with templates and tips.  Canva is also great for creating presentations and infographics.\n\n**V. Financial Aid & Scholarships:**\n\n*   **FAFSA (Free Application for Federal Student Aid):** (Free) The first step in applying for federal student aid.\n*   **Scholarships.com/Fastweb/Chegg:** (Free) Scholarship search engines.\n\n**VI. Health & Well-being:**\n\n*   **Headspace/Calm:** (Free trials, paid subscriptions) Meditation and mindfulness apps.\n*   **Sleep Cycle:** (Free and paid options) Sleep tracking app.\n\n**VII. Textbook & Study Aids**\n\n*   **Chegg:** (Paid subscription) Textbook rentals, homework help, and study tools.\n*   **Quizlet:** (Free and paid options) Flashcard and study game platform.\n*   **Slader/Quizplus:** (Paid subscription) Textbook solutions and homework help.  Be careful not to simply copy answers.  Use these as a way to check your work and understand the concepts.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **University Resources:** Always prioritize the resources offered by your university or college. They often provide free access to databases, software, and tutoring services.\n*   **Free vs. Paid:** Many websites offer free versions or trials. Take advantage of these to see if the platform meets your needs before committing to a paid subscription.\n*   **Privacy:** Be mindful of your privacy when using online tools. Review the privacy policies of websites and apps before sharing personal information.\n*   **Critical Thinking:**  Especially when using resources like Wikipedia or Chegg, practice critical thinking.  Verify information with multiple sources and use study aids to understand the material, not just copy answers.\n*   **Time Management:** While these tools are helpful, don't let them become a distraction.  Set boundaries and use them strategically to improve your productivity.\n\nThis list should give you a great starting point for finding useful websites to support your academic journey. Good luck!\n",
